Today marks a week since I had one of the worst nights/couple of days ever, where I thought I was going to lose my boy.

I ended up rushing Beau to the vets late Tuesday evening where he needed emergency surgery for a severe form of Bloat called GVD.

Whilst in surgery, the vet found a plastic strawberry shaped yoghurt pot that Beau has clearly swallowed out on a walk.
She proceeded to removed the pot, remove part of Beau‚Äôs Stomach that had deteriorated because of said pot, untwist his stomach and attach it to his abdominal wall to prevent future GVD events. 
His spleen was also removed as it was very swollen and had a lesion.
On top of this, his kidney function wasn‚Äôt looking too good understandably.
Queue a very long, scary, sleepless night for me and a painful solitary night for the Sausage.
Beau is an old boy. In fact, he had his 13th birthday the day before his emergency op.
Despite his age. Beau put up the biggest fight and pulled through. 
Queue 48 hours of critical observation where Beau just slept and silently fought all the way.

He‚Äôs made steady progress and I could not be prouder or astounded by him.

I cannot express my gratitude to the medical team who saved my baby,  enough.
My family and friends have been amazingly supportive, including my mum came over when I was having a wobble whilst my dad held down the fort. 

Here‚Äôs to hopefully being signed off on his next check up and to make lots more happy memories with the Sausage. 
üêæüê∂‚ù§Ô∏è

my all time favorite, Spaghetti alla Nerano: spaghetti with zucchiniüáÆüáπ using my bucatini lunghi that @thegiadzy was so kind to send to me! grab your own using the link in my bio‚ú® 

thinly slice 2-4 zucchini 
to a pan add a generous amount of olive oil and heat on high 
fry your zucchini until golden brown- allowing the oil to drip off before adding them to a bowl 
place the bowl of fried zucchini in the fridge for at about an hour 
cook your pasta 2 mins less than recommended cooking time 
while thats boiling, add your fried zucchini to a deep frying pan, allow to warm through on medium high
add 1 tbsp butter 
add your pasta to the pan with the zucchini with 2-3 ladles of pasta water 
toss well and allow the pasta to finish cooking 
once cooked through and the water has been absorbed, add 1/2 cup of grated pecorino and black pepper 
toss well and serve!

a simple dinner .. One Pot Chicken and Rice with parm and peas ‚ú® 

to a large skillet, cook 1 pound of chicken in 2 tbsp of butter, seasoned in salt, about 4 mins each side over medium high heat. 
once golden, remove the chicken set it aside and lower the heat to medium. 
in the same pan, saut√© 1 large red onion and two tbsp of garlic, season with salt. once tender, mix in 1 cup of dry basamati rice and 1/2 tsp of red pepper flakes, allow that to toast for 2 mins. add in 1 cup of mix, 1/2 cup of chicken broth, a piece of parm, and a good sprinkle of dried thyme. add the chicken and its juices back into the pot, cover and allow to simmer on low for 15 mins. once the rice is cooked, fluff with a fork and add in 1 cup of frozen peas. remove from heat and cover the pot to allow the peas to steam. mix finish with olive olive and a good amount of grated parm 
#chicken #chickenandrice #dinner #onepotmeals #easyrecipe

homemade Italian Wedding Soup‚ú®‚ù§Ô∏èüáÆüáπ 

to make the meatballs, mix together 
1 pound of meatloaf mix
3/4 cup of italian breadcrumb
2 eggs 
1/4 cup of grated parm
3 tbsp of dried parsley
1 tsp of garlic powder 
1 tsp of salt 
1 tsp of pepper 
once combined, use about 1 tbsp per meatball and roll in your hands to shape
In a large pan over medium high heat, sear your meatballs in olive oil until browned on all sides. Set aside while on a paper towel lined plate. 

For the Soup, 
in a large pot over medium high heat, saut√© one chopped medium yellow onion, 3 chopped large carrots, and 3 chopped celery stalks. season with salt and pepper and saut√© for 3-5 mins before adding in 2 tbsp of minced garlic. 
Once veggies are fragrant and tender, stir in 1 and 1/4 cup of uncooked Acini de Pepe pasta. 
Deglaze the pot with 1/3 cup of dry white wine and stir until evaporated. (optional: mix in 1 packet of Lipton recipe secrets onion soup packet) 
Add in 2 32 oz boxes of veggie broth, 2 bay leaves, your mini meatballs, a parmesan rind, and about 2-3 cups of chopped escarole. 
cover and bring to a boil and then lower to simmer for 30 mins. Enjoy with fresh grated parm on top!

autumn is for baking and new chocolate chip cookie recipes! üç™üçÇ oh and this one is here to stay.. soft and chewy perfection! 

recipe by our queen @joannagaines ü´∂üèº 

in a medium bowl, whisk together 
2 1/2 cups of flour 
1 heaping tsp of baking soda 
1/2 tsp of salt 
set aside. 
to a stand mixer with a paddle attachment, beat 
1 stick (8tbsp) of butter 
2 cups of packed light brown sugar
once combined, add in 
2 eggs 
1 1/2 tsp of vanilla
beat until blended. 
turn off the mixer and add your flour mixture to the bowl. mix on low to medium until flour is just combined
add in your semisweet chocolate chips about 1 1/2 cups ish (measure with love) 
mix on medium high until combined (about 5 seconds) 
scoop your dough onto a lined baking sheet ( I used a medium sized scoop) dont flatten the dough!
bake at 350 for 8-10 mins or until lightly browned. allow cookies to cool for about a minute or two on the pan before transferring to a cooling rack to cool completely! 

#baking #cookie #cookies #chocolate #chocolatechip #fall #autumn #easy #easyrecipe #dessert #magnolia #recipe #homemade #fallbaking

fall is here so naturally we are craving our fave comfort dishes! first up is my poppop's Beef Stew! ü´∂üèºüçÇ simple and hearty and easy to make! 

brown 1 lb of beef cubes in a dutch oven or deep pot in some olive oil
season with salt, pepper, and dried parsley 
add in the half of 1 large onion chopped and 3-4 peeled and chopped carrots, cook for 10 mins
season with 1 tbsp garlic powder, 1 tsp dried garlic, and 1/4 cup flour
add in your potatoes (I used sweet potatoes and rustic potatoes)
32 oz beef stock
cover and bring to a boil
reduce heat and let it simmer for 1 hour 15 mins once potatoes and beef are tender, 
add in your frozen veg about 
1/2 cup frozen peas
1/2 cup corn 
1/2 lima beans 
stir in
2 bay leaves
1/3 cup ketchup or tomato paste mix and simmer for 10-20 mins! 

#beefstew #stew #soup #souprecipe #fall #autumn #dinner #dinneridea #easy #easyrecipe #easymeals

Ingredients:
1 cup sugar
1.5 cups brown sugar
2 tsp salt
2 sticks melted unsalted butter
2 eggs
2 tsp vanilla extract
2.5 cups all purpose flour
1 tsp baking soda
2 cups chocolate chips

mix together both sugars and salt add in the melted butter and mix then add in the eggs and vanilla extract and mix until it‚Äôs combined and looks like golden ribbons. On a piece of parchment paper sift together your flour and baking soda mix for five seconds and then fold gently with a spatula now add in your chocolate chips and fold until combined. Use a cookie scoop so that each cookie will be similar shape and size and cook evenly place the cookie dough on your cookie sheet and refrigerate for 30 minutes. Preheat your oven to 350¬∞ and bake the cookies for 15 minutes. Let cool on a wire rack and enjoy!

"All the headlights, all the midnights, chasing all that empty, still ain't got it right. All the crazy, all the gypsy. Well, I guess all I'm sayin' is forgive me if I don't know what I'm doing.. I'm still learnin' to be human." -@codyjohnson

I prayed for this man for 33 years. I wished for this man for 33 years. I longed for this man for 33 years. Since I was a wittle babe, I dreamed of having a relationship like my grandma and grandpa. I honestly never thought I was good enough for it. People (mainly men) had spoke so much negative in me throughout the years. How could I ever be worthy enough of a man like this? But man, I was so wrong. It took me 10 years of changing who I was, and what I thought I deserved to end up here.. but it was more than worth it!

This pregnancy has been SO hard on me. I've been a shit wife, mom, friend, employee, etc during these last 12 weeks but you would never be able to tell. (Well my employer can tell but hey. Lol). This man has picked up allllll the slack at home and with the kids, he's driven my summer school route until he ended up with a permanent one, he's gone to the hospital with me for hours on end each time for me to get fluids, he was by my side during my iron infusion, he's there at every doctor's appointment, gone out and bought me ginger ale, made me soup, and soooo much more. And this man NEVER wavers, never complains, never takes short cuts, nothing. I would have not been able to survive some of these days without him. The kids and I are beyond blessed to have him in our lives, and I couldn't ever put words together to thank him or tell him how much we love him.‚ù§Ô∏è

Please join in me in wishing the happiest of birthdays to my ultra mega magnificent, beautiful wife Josephine,
the woman I adore beyond words.

Today may be the day the universe gave birth to you, but every day I‚Äôm the one receiving the gift.Your soul, your light, your imagination, your devotion, they are blessings I get to wake up to each morning.

Thank you for being my partner,
my companion, my safe place,
my laughter, my softness,
my adventure, my home.

From Thailand to Hawaii to soon to be Bali,
from our real estate licenses to motorcycle permits, from forever continuing classes for growth,
to the home and creations we‚Äôve built together, especially the simple little things that mean the most‚Ä¶ Our love for art, our long nights painting in silence, our sunsets on the lanai with the boys, our family walks, marathon nights with popcorn, our thrift-store treasure hunts, our woodworking experiments, our new inventions, our wild ideas, all of it becomes magic simply because it‚Äôs with you.

So on this blessed day,
I celebrate your birth with oceans of love,
tsunamis of kisses, and endless waves of gratitude.

Know how much you complete me
not by filling a void,
but by expanding my world
into something wider, deeper, and more magical.

Love from the deep ends of the sea where the misfit creatures lye happily ‚ú®Your beloved wife ‚ù§Ô∏è‚Äçüî•

We want to remind you to live your life fully and authentically, no matter what anyone thinks or says about your story. One day, we‚Äôll all look back on these moments, and what will matter most is that you honored your own desires, your own joy, and your own truth.

Stand tall. Love fiercely. Live freely.

üõí‚ú® Just released: The Shopper‚Äôs Guide to Arthur Avenue ‚Äî your ultimate companion to NYC‚Äôs real Little Italy. Today we laid my mom to rest. 

You were the greatest Mom a son could ask for. You guided me and always put me in position to succeed and when I got knocked down you pushed me to get back up. Your advice was something so many sought after because of how wise you were. It can‚Äôt be put into words what you meant to my life and so many others. You embody what it means to be strong, nothing broke you and that is something I got to see firsthand. 

You truly defined what it means to be incredible. 

And I know you are still here with me every single day guiding me from above. 

To my mom and best friend. Thank you for everything you did and continue to do. 

I love you and miss you. This will not be easy, but I will continue to make you proud. 

Until we meet again Mama.

Prosciutto Bread. Recipe ‚¨áÔ∏è Ingredients:

1 cup warm water
1 tsp. granulated sugar
1 package active dry yeast (1/4 ounce)
2 1/4 cups bread flour
2 tsp. ground black pepper
1/2 tsp. salt
3 tbsp. lard, melted (see notes)
3/4 lb provolone cheese, cubed
3/4 lb. prosciutto, cubed
Olive oil
You will need a stand mixer for this recipe. In the bowl of the mixer fitted with a dough hook, stir together the water and sugar. Sprinkle the yeast on top and stir again. Set aside for 5 minutes, or until the yeast is foamy. If the yeast doesn‚Äôt foam, the yeast is likely expired, so you will need to discard the mixture and start over again.  Take one tbsp. of melted lard and add to bowl. Place the rest of the melted lard off to the side for use later. 

Add flour, salt, and pepper to bowl. Attach dough hook and turn mixer on medium. Mix dough for about 10 mins. Dough should be sticking to the bottom of the bowl - if it seems too sticky, you can add one tbsp. of flour as needed. 

When dough is formed, stop mixer and add the cheese and prosciutto. Mix on low/medium until meat and cheese are equally incorporated. 

Brush a large bowl with 2 tablespoons of the olive oil. Transfer the dough to the bowl. Cover the bowl with plastic wrap or a towel and set aside until the dough has doubled in size, about 1 hour. Flour parchment paper and remove dough to paper. Using your hands, roll the dough out into a long log, about 15‚Äù long. Twist the dough log from one end to the next to form little cracks in the surface of the dough. Think of the pattern of a candy cane. 

Form the log into a circle by connecting both ends of the log. Your dough should now look like a wreath. 

Cover dough again with a towel for another hour. Remove towel and brush an additional tbsp. of melted lard over the top and sides of the dough. If your lard has solidified at all, you may need to melt it again so it‚Äôs totally liquified. Lift edges of parchment paper to transfer loaf onto a pizza stone or a large cast iron surface. Place on the middle oven rack and bake at 400 degrees for 30-35 minutes, until golden brown

RECIPE (2 servings)
[A] NOODLES‚Ä®„Éª350g shirataki konnyaku‚Ä®„Éª1 tbsp sugar
[B] CHICKEN‚Ä®„Éª150g ground chicken‚Ä®„Éª1/2 tsp garlic paste‚Ä®„Éª1/2 tsp grated ginger‚Ä®„Éª1 tsp gochujang (adjust to taste)‚Ä®„Éª1 tsp chili bean sauce (optional)

[D] TOPPINGS (optional)‚Ä®„ÉªGreen onions‚Ä®„ÉªWhite sesame‚Ä®„ÉªChili oil
HOW TO MAKE
	1.	Rinse shirataki, cut if too long.
	2.	Massage with sugar ‚Üí let it sit 10‚Äì15 min to reduce the smell.
	3.	Cook chicken and season based on your spice tolerance ‚Äî set aside.
	4.	Mix soup base ingredients in a pot.
	5.	Rinse shirataki again, drain well, then add to soup.
	6.	Heat gently (don‚Äôt fully boil or soy milk will split), add chicken back in.
	7.	Serve and top with your [D] toppings. Enjoy!

Welcome to my Japanese food fermentation era starring the star of Japanese cooking, KOJI! ‚ú®

If you‚Äôre new here, hiii üëã I‚Äôm Lina and I‚Äôm currently studying to get my food fermentation instructor license. Safe to say I‚Äôm a little obsessed with all things koji üç∂üçö

Koji is really the backbone of Japanese cooking ‚Äî I t‚Äôs the mold that ferments your favorite ingredients like soy sauce, miso, mirin and sake. All that umami magic comes from koji‚Äôs enzymes! 

Today we‚Äôre making shio koji (Â°©È∫π), one of my cooking staples. Think of it like an elevated salt seasoning that‚Äôs slightly sweet, great for your gut and packed with umami.

One of the tools I use to ferment is the @gohan_japan_tanica YOGURTiA machine. I‚Äôm SO excited they‚Äôve officially started selling their products in the U.S. on Amazon like their rice koji too! üõí 
Use code TANICALINA10 for 10% off the YOGURTiA and rice koji this month (link in bio)üéâ

I can‚Äôt wait to share more koji recipes and show you the meals you can make with shio koji! Comment if you have any questions, I‚Äôd love to dive into it with you üí¨

SHIO KOJI RECIPE

200g dried rice koji
60g salt
250ml water

1. Sanitize your YOGURTiA jar and utensils.
2. Thoroughly mix the rice koji, salt and water in the glass pot.
3. Place lids and put into the YOGURTiA.
4. Set to 140F for 6 hours.
5. It‚Äôs ready when the rice koji crushes easily between your fingers.
6. Transfer to a clean jar and refrigerate for up to 3 months, stirring occasionally.

(Recipe from the YOGURTiA recipe guide)

This is a very simple pork dish that‚Äôs just simmered. 
You can use it in sandwiches or fried rice, but it‚Äôs especially recommended as a topping for ramen!

Japanese-style Braised Pork
Ingredients for 3-4 servings¬†
- 400‚Äì500g (1 lb)¬† pork shoulder (block)
- 500ml sparkling water„ÄÄ(about 2 cups)
- green onion tops
- three slices of ginger

- 2 Tbsp. sugar
- 2 Tbsp. sake
- 2 Tbsp. soy sauce¬†

1.Put the pork shoulder, sparkling water, the green tops of the green onion, and the sliced ginger in a pot, and simmer over medium-low heat for 20 minutes. Skim off the foam occasionally and flip it halfway through.

2. Add sugar, sake, and soy sauce, then cover with parchment paper. Simmer over medium-low heat for 10 minutes, flip the meat, and simmer for another 10 minutes. Continue simmering until the liquid has reduced.

3. Once cooled, slice thinly. Arrange on a plate and pour the cooking liquid over.

Have you tried Japanese sweet potatoes? Their inside is creamy yellow and they are very sweet! In Japan, we enjoy many kinds of sweet potato desserts. Please give them a try.¬†¬†

Sweet Potato Cakes (makes 12 pieces)
Ingredients:
- 400g sweet potato (peeled)
- 60g sugar
- 40g butter
- 3 Tbsp. heavy cream

- 1 tsp. to  1 Tbsp. rum (optional)¬†¬†
- 1¬Ω egg yolks

¬†Egg wash¬†¬†
- ¬Ω egg yolk
- 2 tsp. milk

¬†1ÔºéPeel the sweet potatoes and cut them into pieces, then soak them in water for about 15 minutes.¬† Steam the sweet potatoes for about 20 minutes, until they become soft. ¬†

ÔºíÔºé Separate ¬Ω egg yolk and mix it with milk to make an egg wash.

ÔºìÔºé Place the sweet potatoes, sugar, butter, heavy cream and rum in a blender and blend until smooth. Stop once, add the egg yolks, and blend again.

ÔºîÔºé Fit a star-shaped nozzle onto a piping bag and fill it with the sweet potato mixture. Line 12 cups on a baking sheet and pipe the mixture into each cup.

ÔºïÔºé Gently brush the surface with egg wash. Bake in a 210¬∞C (410¬∞F) oven for about 15 minutes, until golden brown. They are delicious when chilled before serving!

Do you know sukiyaki? It‚Äôs a savory and sweet simmered dish that Japanese people eat on special occasions, such as celebrations. I made a sukiyaki bowl ‚Äî it‚Äôs easier to cook!

Sukiyaki bowl
Ingredients for 2 servings
- 1/4 onion
- 110 g Chinese cabbage (1/4 lb)
- 140 g firm tofu (5 oz)
- 1/2 shimeji mushroom
- 2 tsp. oil
- 110g Thinly sliced beef(1/4lb)
- 1 and 1/2 Tbsp. brown sugar
- 1 Tbsp. sake
- 1 and 1/2 Tbsp. soy sauce
- 2 eggs
- 170g cooked rice (6 oz)√ó2
- pickled red ginger (optional)

Instructions
1. Slice the onion. Roughly chop the Chinese cabbage. Remove the stems from the shimeji mushrooms. Cut the tofu into cubes.
2. Heat oil in a frying pan and stir-fry the beef until its color changes slightly. Remove the meat from the pan and set aside.
3. Add the onion, Chinese cabbage, tofu, and shimeji mushrooms, and lightly stir-fry. Add the seasonings, cover with a lid, and simmer over low heat for 4 minutes.
4. Return the beef to the pan and crack the eggs in. Cover with a lid and simmer over low heat for 3 minutes.
5. Set up two rice bowls and place the ingredients on each. Garnish with pickled red ginger if you like, and it‚Äôs ready to serve.

Tips
„ÉªStir-frying the beef first allows its flavor to remain in the pan.
„ÉªTo prevent the beef from becoming too tough, set it aside after cooking.
„ÉªShiitake or enoki mushrooms can be used as a substitute for shimeji.

Do you like teriyaki chicken?
This dish is wrapped in a Mexican tortilla.
The sweet and savory teriyaki flavor goes perfectly with it!
You can find the teriyaki chicken recipe in one of my previous posts.¬†¬†

Ingredients for 1 serving
- 1 serving teriyaki chicken(from another recipe)
- 1 tortilla
- a handful of lettuce
- 2 tsp. teriyaki sauce
- half an avocado
- a little red onion
- some mayonnaise

Instructions
1. Make teriyaki chicken while referring to the teriyaki chicken recipe.
2. Dice the avocado and thinly slice the red onion.
3. Place lettuce, teriyaki chicken, teriyaki sauce, avocado, and red onion on the tortilla. Finally, drizzle with mayonnaise and roll it up.
4. Wrap it tightly from the top with plastic wrap. Let it sit for about 10 minutes, then cut in half to serve.

Tips
„ÉªThe teriyaki chicken recipe is introduced separately.

„ÉªPlease use the leftover teriyaki sauce from when you made the chicken.

This recipe uses¬†Tono Dressing, a popular product at Japanese grocery stores.@tono_dressing
Tono Dressing is packed with¬†truffle flavor and rich umami, and it goes perfectly with mushrooms.
So this time, I made a hamburger with plenty of mushrooms to bring out that delicious combination.

In Japan, adding breadcrumbs to hamburger patties is a common and popular way to make them juicy and tender.
This burger turns out so flavorful ‚Äî I hope you‚Äôll give it a try!

This recipe was created by¬†Zono.
I post simple Japanese home-style recipes on Instagram.¬†¬†
@japan.diet.recipe

Ingredients for the Hamburger Patties (4 servings)
- 1 lb (450g) ground beef
- 1/2 onion
- 10 mushrooms
- 3 Tbsp bread crumbs
- 1/2 tsp salt
- black pepper
- 1 egg
- 2 tsp oil
- 2 Tbsp water
- 2 Tbsp Tono dressing (for the patties)

For One Hamburger
- Burger buns
- Tono dressing ‚Äî as needed
- Lettuce
- Tomato
-mayonnaise

Instructions
1.Slice the onion into rings and remove four of the outer rings. Finely chop the inner part. Slice the mushrooms thickly.

2.In a bowl, combine the ground beef, bread crumbs, egg, salt, and black pepper. Mix well, then add the chopped onion and mix again. Shape the mixture into flat round patties.

3.Heat oil in a frying pan and place the patties in it. Cover and cook over medium heat for 3 minutes. Once browned, flip and cook for another 2 minutes.

4.When both sides are browned, add the mushrooms and place the onion rings on top of the patties. Add water, cover, and cook over low heat for 10 minutes.

5.Remove the onions, pour in the Tono dressing, and coat the patties and mushrooms evenly.

6.Spread Tono dressing on both sides of the burger buns and lightly toast them. Place lettuce on the bottom bun, then put the onion ring on top and fill it with mushrooms. Add the hamburger patty and tomato slice, spread mayonnaise on top, and cover with the upper bun.

This recipe is featured in Nijiya‚Äôs magazine. Sweet potatoes are rich in vitamin C and dietary fiber. The kinako„ÄÄcoating is made from soybeans, which are a great source of protein and calcium. Since these cookies are mostly made from sweet potatoes, you can really enjoy their moist, soft texture. Please give them a try!

Sweet Potato and Kinako Cube Cookies
Ingredients¬†(Serves 4)
- Sweet potato (peeled): 60g
- Nijiya Brand cake flour: 80g
- Powdered sugar: 60g
- Salted butter: 50g
- Kinako (roasted soybean flour): 1 tbsp
- Sugar: as needed

Instructions

Preparation:
Preheat the oven to 160¬∞C (320¬∞F).

Cut the sweet potato into bite-sized pieces and place them in a heatproof bowl. Cover with plastic wrap and microwave for about 2‚Äì3 minutes, until soft enough to mash. Mash with a fork and let cool.

In a food processor, combine the cake flour and powdered sugar, and pulse lightly. Add the diced butter and process until no butter chunks remain. Add the mashed sweet potato and process until the dough starts to come together. Wrap the dough and chill in the refrigerator for about 1 hour.

Dust your work surface with some flour (extra, not included in the ingredient list). Roll out the dough into a square about 1.5 cm thick. Cut into small cubes with a knife.

Line a baking sheet with parchment paper and arrange the dough cubes. Bake at 160¬∞C (320¬∞F) for about 15 minutes. Let them cool on a wire rack.

In a tray, mix kinako and sugar (to taste), then coat the cooled cookies with the mixture. Enjoy!

Tips:
Baking time may vary depending on your oven, so adjust as needed.
If you don‚Äôt have a food processor, follow the same steps using your hands‚Äîrub the butter into the flour mixture until crumbly, then mix in the mashed sweet potato.
You can adjust the sweetness by changing the amount of sugar you coat the cookies with.

Japanese-Style Sweet and Sour Meatballs

¬†Ingredients (Serves 3‚Äì4)

- 200g¬† ¬†Ground pork
- 200g¬† ¬†Ground chicken
- 1/3 stalk (about 30 g)¬† Green onion (white part)¬†
- 1/3 tsp¬† ¬†Salt¬†
-1/2¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬†Egg¬†¬†
- 2Tbsp.¬† Bread crumbs¬†
- 1 clove¬† Grated ginger ‚Ä¶¬†
Potato starch¬† ¬†as needed

Sweet and Sour Sauce
-¬† 2 Tbsp¬† Ketchup¬†¬†
-¬† 2 Tbsp¬† Water¬†
-¬† 1 and 1/2 tbsp¬† Sugar¬†
- 1 Tbsp.¬† Soy sauce¬†
-¬† 2 tsp¬† ¬†Vinegar ‚Ä¶¬†

Topping

Instructions

1. Mince the green onion and grate the ginger.

4.Line a large frying pan (with a lid) with a sheet of parchment paper that‚Äôs been crumpled and then spread out. Arrange the meatballs on top, pour some water underneath the paper, cover with a lid, and heat. Once it starts boiling, reduce to low heat and steam for about 15 minutes.

Mackerel is rich in unsaturated fatty acids such as¬†DHA¬†and¬†EPA, and it‚Äôs also a good source of¬†vitamin D, which helps strengthen your bones.
When you serve it with eggplant cooked in a sweet and savory teriyaki sauce over rice, it becomes a truly delicious and satisfying dish.

Teriyaki Mackerel and Eggplant Rice Bowl
Ingredients for 2 servings
- 1¬† Eggplant¬†
-¬† 1 piece (about 160 g)¬† ¬†Mackerel fillet¬†
- 1 Tbsp.¬† Potato starch¬†
- 2 tsp. Oil (for eggplant)¬†
- 2 tsp.¬† Oil (for mackerel)¬†
-¬† 2 bowls¬† ¬†Cooked rice¬†
-¬† 2 Shiso leaves ‚Ä¶¬† finely chopped

Sauce (Teriyaki Mixture)
-¬† 1 tbsp + 1 tsp¬† ¬†Soy sauce 
- 1 Tbsp. Sugar¬†
- 1 Tbsp. Mirin¬†
- 1 Tbsp. Water¬†

Instructions
1.Slice the eggplant lengthwise into thick pieces (about 2 cm wide) and soak them in water for a few minutes.

2.Pat the mackerel dry with paper towels to remove excess moisture. Cut into bite-size pieces and coat evenly with potato starch.

3.Heat 2 tsp of oil in a frying pan. Add the eggplant and cook over medium-low heat until both sides are browned and tender. Remove from the pan and set aside.

4.In the same pan, add 2 tsp of oil and cook the mackerel, turning occasionally, until both sides are golden and crispy. Once cooked through, turn off the heat and add the eggplant and the teriyaki sauce mixture. Turn the heat back on and simmer until the sauce thickens and coats everything nicely.

5.Serve the rice in two bowls, place the mackerel and eggplant on top, drizzle the remaining sauce over, and garnish with chopped shiso leaves.

Nijiya Market, a Japanese grocery store in the U.S., featured my recipes and column in their magazine.
The theme is vitamins and minerals that are often lacking in our diet.
I created four recipes that help you get more nutrients such as vitamin D, iron, and calcium.
I‚Äôll be sharing videos of these recipes soon!

Have you ever tried¬†takikomi gohan?
It‚Äôs a popular Japanese rice dish cooked with various ingredients. 
You can add your favorite ones and make your own version!

takikomi gohan¬† Japanese Mixed Rice

Ingredients for 2 servings
-300g Japanese rice(1.6cups)
-2 pieces of aburaage (fried tofu pouches)
-1 pack of shimeji mushrooms
-100g chicken breast (0.22 lb)
-1 Tbsp. sake
-340 ml Dashi (1.4 cups)
-2 Tbsp. soy sauce

Instructions
1. Wash the rice and soak it in fresh water for 30 minutes.

2. Cut the aburaage (fried tofu pouch) in half lengthwise, then slice thinly. Pour boiling water over it to remove excess oil, drain in a colander, and squeeze out the„ÄÄmoisture.„ÄÄ

3. Trim off the base of the shimeji mushrooms and separate them into small clusters.

4. Cut the chicken into bite-sized pieces and sprinkle with sake.

5. Place the drained rice in a pot with a lid. Add dashi and soy sauce, and stir lightly. Then add the chicken, shimeji mushrooms, and aburaage on top.

6. Cover the pot with the lid slightly ajar and cook over medium heat. After about 5 minutes, when it comes to a boil, close the lid completely, reduce the heat to low, and cook for 12 minutes. Increase the heat to medium for just 10 seconds, then turn off the heat and let it rest, covered, for 10 minutes.

Tips
„ÉªJapanese rice tastes better when you soak it in water for 30 minutes after washing, as it absorbs moisture.

„ÉªTo remove the excess oil on the surface of aburaage (fried tofu), it‚Äôs best to pour boiling water over it or briefly boil it.

„ÉªThis time I used simple ingredients, but you can also add your favorites such as bamboo shoots, carrots, or burdock root.

Have you ever tried a type of squash that‚Äôs popular in Asia?
It has green skin and bright orange flesh inside.
Because it‚Äôs naturally sweet, it‚Äôs often used not only in savory dishes and soups but also in desserts.
This custard is baked slowly in the oven, which gives it an incredibly smooth texture.

I hope you‚Äôll give it a try!¬†¬†

Kabocha custard

Ingredients for 4 servings
- 1/8 kabocha squash ÔºàUse 80 grams of mashed itÔºâ
- 2 tsp. water
- 1 egg yolk
- 1 egg
- 40g sugar
- Cinnamon(optional)
- 240ml (1 cup) milk

Caramel sauce
- 20g sugar
- 3 Tbsp. water
- 20ml hot water

Instructions
1. Scoop out the kabocha seeds and peel the skin. Cut it into bite-sized pieces and place them in a heatproof bowl. Microwave for about 2 minutes, or until tender.

2. Mash with a fork and pass through a strainer. At this point, prepare 80 grams (3 oz) of strained kabocha.

3. In a bowl, combine the mashed kabocha with sugar, egg yolk, and an egg, and whisk well.

4. Add milk and mix further. If you like cinnamon, add it to taste.

5. After straining, divide the mixture among four heatproof cups.

6. Cover each cup with aluminum foil. Place the cups on a baking tray and pour about 2 cm of hot water into the tray. Bake at 160¬∞C(320‚Ñâ) for 35‚Äì40 minutes. The custard is done when the surface is set and firm to a gentle shake. Let it cool in the refrigerator before serving.

7. Make caramel sauce. In a saucepan, combine sugar and water and bring to a boil. When it turns brown, remove from heat and carefully add hot water. Pour the caramel over the chilled custard just before serving.

Tips
„ÉªKabocha is very hard, so be careful not to cut your fingers. If you microwave it for about 1 minute before use, it will soften and be easier to cut.

„ÉªStraining the mixture gives it a smooth texture.

„ÉªThe caramel sauce recipe was introduced before in my pudding recipe.

-Vietkane Featherback Fish Paste
-Scallions
-Salt 
-Sugar
-Black Pepper
-Garlic
-Thai chilies
-Lime
-Cilantro

1. Boil vermicelli according to package instructions, rinse in cold water. Save water, add in scallion whites, boil again, and blanch squid for 1-2 minutes, beef for 30 seconds, remove and set aside. 
2. To make dipping sauce, mince garlic and chili, then combine with sugar, salt, pepper, lime juice, and zest of one lime. Set aside.
3. In a food processor, combine shrimp, roughly chopped scallions, salt, and blend until it forms a paste.
4. Repeat for fish paste.
5. Boil water in a kettle. In a big bowl, smear fish and shrimp paste onto the inside of the bowl, one at a time, until it‚Äôs a thin layer. Pour boiling water directly on the paste, wait for a few minutes and gently scrape off the slabs.
6. Save liquid until all the paste is used. Season liquid with salt.
7. Assemble vermicelli, beef, squid, shrimp paste, fish paste, in a bowl and top with lots of scallions and cilantro.
8. Pour in hot seafood liquid. Spoon a little bit of dipping sauce in the bowl and serve the rest on the side.

posts.caption:
day 2 of making cookies that get progressively harder: thrice baked rye cookies

recipe from dessert person by @csaffitz 

if you wanna read all the lessons and tips i learned for this bake, check out my newsletter (link in bio) or at: aneskim.substack.com üíõ

okay i've been wanting to make this cookie for so long now (the rye flour's been sitting in my pantry for MONTHS) but the name "thrice-baked" intimidated me. It sounds like a lot of work!

turns out it took much much longer than day 1's drop cookies but i think i learned a lot from this recipe. like using boiled eggs for cookie dough? 

i've got to say these are one of my favorite things ive made this year and are SO ADDICTING. i gave some to my mom and she said they were gone in a minute üòÇ even thought this recipe is a bit fussy with all the steps, i can't wait to make this one again soon ü§≠

tomorrow is going to be a bit of a twist from your "average" cookie so stay tuned!

#baking #beginnerbaker #learningtobake #cookies #rye #dessertperson #cookierecipe #cookie

ep. 18 - salty nut tart from dessert person!

still a noob at making tart crusts so this was kinda scary seeing a huge crack in the middle :0 but it really worked out and i'm glad the recipe guided me through the repair process!

i've got to say that this flavor combination was lovely, something about the caramel, nuts and the rosemary go so well together it was absolutely addicting to eat. and i really really liked how buttery this crust was! much much better than the one i made for the GBBO technical series heh. we're making progress on the tart crusts yay :)

#dessertperson #tart #baking #bake #dessert

ep. 17 - chocolate chip cookies from dessert person!

what kind of chocolate chip cookie do you like? 

personally anything chewy and not to sweet is my fav but this recipe's brown butter flavor caught my eye :0 

i'd say the extra step of browning the butter is worth it because it adds so much complexity in flavor that compliments the chocolate so well! something to note for future cookie testing hehe

#dessertperson #chocolatechipcookie #cookie #cookierecipe #cookies

ep. 16 - Italian Plum Galette from Dessert Person

i've never tried italian plums before so i didn't know what to expect from flavor, but i was so bright and tart and absolutely lovely :)

i do think that cutting the butter cubes much smaller and using a dough blender kind of helped - maybe next time i need to let the dough sit for a bit before i roll it out. 

i do think this flavor combination was really cool though, i would have never thought to use polenta with plums - so happy i got to attempt this one so cheers!

#dessertperson #baking #galette #plums #dessert #learningtobake

GBBO technical week 5 - white chocolate tart!

omg i am so embarrassed to post this video but another part of me is like hey! stuff like this happens and it can be a fun experience to learn from too :) 

i truly did not expect the curd to be that inedible HAHA i was a bit surprised - it kind of tasted like grainy, mushy, not sweet curd? so not my best work but now i know not to overwhisk and use REALLY ripe fruit if i can!

i also forgot to poke the tart dough before it went into the oven haha so it did inflate a bit! anyways, it was cool getting to bake with passionfruit because that was my first time! 

#gbbo #technicalbake #greatbritishbakeoff #baking #tart #learningtobake

GBBO technical week 4 - school cake and custard!

i CANNOT make this up i literally was mixing the cake batter and saw a bowl of sugar just sitting there and i was like - oh goodness how could i miss SUGAR in cake ah! 

i feel like pound cake has been quite forgiving in the past, considering the times i've made the butter and egg curdled (lol) so i was like i'm just gonna go with it - and not bad! surprisingly good considering the order of operations haha.

i also made my icing much thicker this time and it turned out much more opaque which i liked too so yay for improvement :)

#gbbo #baking #bake #cake #custard #greatbritishbakeoff

GBBO technical week 3 - Glazed Donuts!

okay this timing came perfectly because ya girl has been craving donuts (glazed in particular) BUT i feel like my execution was definitely a bit off haha

i don't particularly love frying foods (because hot oil scares me lol if you've seen my yakgwa video) but i will say getting to see the dessert cook in front of you is nice since you can monitor the color/doneness much more easily!

I may have to tackle donuts again some other time!

#donuts #gbbo #greatbritishbakeoff #glazeddonuts

ep. 15 - caramelized endive galette!

tbh i had no idea what an endive was or tasted like until this recipe haha. but i was really excited to try this because i've never seen anything like it - salad on a pastry? i was down to try!

i do think i've had radicchio before in restaurants but it was really fun working with that too since i didn't realize how bitter it was until i tried it on its own. 

and talk about caramelizing - was not expecting to stand there for like an hour lol (haha this was my first time) but i KNEW it was going to be worth it in the final flavor. and it totally was :)

#baking #dessertperson #galette #bake #learningtobake #pastry

my attempt at the Great British Bake Off's week 2 technical challenge: chocolate caramel hobnobs :0

was not expecting to struggle this much with rolling out the dough (which seems to be a common trend in all my bakes LOL) but i guess sometimes you just gotta switch things up to make it work!

definitely will need to go back and watch a video on how to make caramel after this because ya girl was STRUGGLING. i was like what the heckins is this when i poured in the butter for the caramel haha! it's a good learning experience though and i'm glad i attempted it at least!

can't wait to follow along for the rest of the series - cheers!

#gbbo #greatbritishbakeoff #technicalbake #baking #bake #hobnob

ep. 14 - double-apple crumble cake from dessert person!

omg i can't believe it's already fall - one of my favorite seasons to bake because it reminds me of all the beautiful warm spice flavors :)

i cannot tell you how SOFT the inside of this cake was. i thought it was going to be mostly apple in each bite, but it was a good mix of both cake and soft apples too! the flavor definitely reminds me of apple pie but it was interesting to eat it in cake form. can't wait to bake more recipes for the fall ah!

#dessertperson #applecake #cake #fallbaking #baking #bake #learningtobake

*spoiler alert if you don't want to know what the technical challenge was for ep. 1!!!*

GBBO 2025 technical - Fondant Fancies

i have not yet watched the newest episode because i wanted to bake this "blind"! so excited to watch this newest season hehe

#britishbakeoff #thegreatbritishbakeoff #baking #bake

ep. 13 - pistachio linzer tart from dessert person!

omg i have been waiting to make this recipe but never got around to it until this series because it just looked so intimidating in the picture! it's actually still marked as easy in terms of level but as soon as i saw the piping my mind was just like nope! overall it wasn't too bad, i think i just needed to put less pistachio batter on the bottom to have more saved for the top.

i will say that i absolultely love this flavor combination and would love to explore other recipes like cakes and things that use this classic combo :)

oh i also called these cookies at the end because they were cut into small pieces but i meant to say linzer tart!

#dessertperson #baking #linzertart #tart #bake #learningtobake #pistachio

posts.caption:
Thanksgiving dinner for a family with an aging parent ‚ù§Ô∏èüçó 

Part 1: Instant pot turkey or chicken that‚Äôs soft & lower sodium for grandma

my partner and I are Caregiver for 85-year-old mom. She required soft and lower sodium food. Which can make meals a bit more complicated. 

So the trick in our house is creating a meal that works for her, but can be slightly altered to work for everybody. 

Turkey is notoriously dry. Of course there‚Äôs plenty of ways to make it more moist, but when it comes to feeding an aging parent, it can be a little bit risky.

So often when I cook, turkey or chicken, I just use the pressure cooker. The instant pot is a very easy way to get super juicy, soft meat with very little effort.

And when you cook a whole turkey or chicken, not only do you get the meat, but you also can make a nice, flavorful broth with it. And then you can also save the bones and leftover scraps for another broth! The gift that keeps on giving. 

So this is how I make a super soft Thanksgiving turkey (or chicken) for a family with an aging parent. 

INSTANT POT TURKEY / CHICKEN

1 whole chicken or small turkey
4 cups low sodium broth
1-2 cups water (until it reaches the max line)
Poultry herbs, ties with twine
6 cloves of garlic, peeled
2 shallots, peeled, cut in half
2 carrots, cut in half
2 celery, cut in half
4 dried mushrooms
1 packet no salt chicken seasoning

DIRECTOINS

Place all ingredients in pressure cooker
Pressure cook on high for 27 minutes
Allow to naturally release for 10 minutes
Remove poultry to cool
Remove meat from bones.  Save bones and scraps in a freezer bag for a future broth
remove veggies and herbs and set aside for gravy

Life at 27 looks WAY different than what I thought it would be. When I was 20-23, I pictured that by now, I would already be working through medical school residency. But here I am, baking cute desserts and creating third-culture recipes. And I wouldn‚Äôt have it any other way!

my mom‚Äôs leche flan recipe üçÆ so silky, creamy, smooth, and delicious! it‚Äôs my go-to dessert to make for family holiday parties, and most of the time, the first one to be finished üòâ

comment ‚ÄúLINK‚Äù to get the free recipe & baking mold link sent to your DMs! (If you‚Äôre a private acct and not following me, it may not go through due to privacy settings)

-

A common question I get asked is‚Ä¶ What is flan?

Flan is a silky custard dessert topped with a rich caramel sauce. It‚Äôs such a beloved dessert that there are many countries around the world with their own version! 

The recipes differ by using whole eggs vs egg yolks, different milks, extracts, etc. And alllll are delicious. If your country has flan, what do they call it and what‚Äôs it made of? üòä

Leche flan is the Filipino version‚Äîa custard made with only egg yolks, condensed milk, evaporated milk, and vanilla. It‚Äôs super creamy, silky, and one of my favorite Filipino classics. If you go to a Filipino party, you‚Äôre bound to find leche flan there.

Not only is it delicious, but it‚Äôs easy to make. Although it might sound intimidating to make your own caramel and custard, it‚Äôs quite simple to prep. And if it‚Äôs your first time making it‚Äîdon‚Äôt worry! My blog post will have all the information you‚Äôll need. üôÇ

-

LMK if you make it! Happy baking.

üêü meat pie for salmon lovers!

These salmon Wellington pastry bites are such a fun and cute appetizer to make for the holidays! They‚Äôre flavorful and filled with omega-3s from @wildplanetfoods Wild sockeye salmon! Enjoy them with my creamy dill sauce for even more protein!

‚ú®Save this because I‚Äôm leaving the recipe below for you to make for your next holiday get together!

#wildplanet #wildplanetpartner #easyrecipes #easyrecipe #pescatarian #tinnedfish #salmonrecipe #salmonwellington #salmonencroute #puffpastry #appetizer #healthyrecipes #asmr 

Ingredients
6oz spinach
4 garlic cloves, minced
1 small shallot, finely minced
Zest of 1 lemon
1/2 tsp salt
1/4 tsp black pepper
1 6oz can Wild Planet wild sockeye salmon, drained
3 oz cream cheese, softened
1/4 cup grated Parmesan cheese
2 sheets puff pastry, thawed
1 egg, beaten
1 tbsp water

Creamy dill sauce
1/2 cup cottage cheese, blended
2 tbsp lemon juice
1/2 tsp salt
3-4 tbsp dill, minced

Instructions
1. In a pan over medium-low heat, add oil and shallots. Saute until softened. Add garlic and cook until fragrant and softened.
2. Add spinach, salt, black pepper, and lemon zest. Give it a mix. Cook, stirring frequently to wilt the spinach. Continue cooking until all the moisture has evaporated, about 8-10 minutes. 
3. Turn the heat to low and add in Wild PlanetWild Sockeye Salmon, breaking up any large clumps. Mix in the cream cheese and parmesan cheese until combined. Remove from heat.
4. Preheat your oven to 400F.
5. Roll out one sheet of puff pastry on a floured board. Place tablespoons of the cooled filling evenly across the pastry, leaving 2 inches of space between each mound.
6. Mix together an egg and water to make an egg wash. Brush the pastry around the filling with egg wash. Carefully add a second sheet of puff pastry on top, gently pushing the pastry down around the filling.

Persimmon Ice Cream üçäüç¶üç®
‚Ä¢	Mix and heat together 1.25 cups of milk and 1 cup heavy cream on the stove
	‚Ä¢	Whisk 4-5 egg yolks with half a cup of sugar
	‚Ä¢	Temper the egg mixture with some of the milk/cream liquid so that it does not cook at the next step
	‚Ä¢	Pour the egg mixture into the milk/cream
	‚Ä¢	Cut up 3-4 persimmons and blend with the milk mix. I used an immersion blender for this step
	‚Ä¢	If it‚Äôs too solid, add a bit more milk
	‚Ä¢	Freeze for 2 hours to overnight
	‚Ä¢	Churn for 18 minutes
	‚Ä¢	Quenelle if feeling fancy, serve with blood orange juice, toasted sweet rice, and pistacio oil
	‚Ä¢	Serve with cinnamon toast crunch cereal, salt, and pistachio oil if feeling fun

Beef tartare with black sesame crisp, mandarin salad, and burrata with speck, stovetop Korean pears and persimmons

The base recipes are from the Four Horsemen cookbook - as we have very Asian leaning palettes, we substituted some ingredients and modified the base recipes to reflect that. 

Beef Tartare modified recipe ü•©:
The ratio is from my butcher who happens to also work at a restaurant. Recommendation is to use 0.25 lbs per serving (serving can be 2 ppl in my opinion)

Thinly dice your preferred amount of eye round roast. Tip I got from the butcher is to place into freezer 30-45 min before cutting but lowkey I did 90 min and it could‚Äôve been a bit longer. Combine with sunflower seeds, salt, Chile oil, and beef fat (rendered). 

Make thickened buttermilk by adding ratio 3:1 butter milk to whipping cream with some salt and 2-4g of gelatin into a warm pot. Cool off and let it thicken in the fridge (overnight but we just did an hour.. bc time crunch)

Garlic chili oil 
Heat your preferred ratio of garlic, chili flakes, oil and salt with a cheesecloth of Sichuan, star anise pods, ginger, cinnamon. This can be taken from the Four Horsemen cookbook, but I think if you default to your preferred taste, it would be better suited. We had ALOT of garlic.

You can use any black sesame cracker recipe online as this is optional.

We chose to remove pickled cabbage from the base recipe

Plate how‚Äôd like :)

I made a Pandan Pavlova ‚Äî to see what happens when you mix Vietnamese flavors with an iconic Australian dessert üç∞üíö

Recipe:
1. Make or buy pandan extract.
To make it: blend pandan leaves with water (3:1 ratio by weight).
2. Strain and store the green liquid overnight in the fridge.
3. Beat 4 egg whites until frothy.
4. Slowly whisk in 120g sugar until glossy and smooth.
5. Add 1 tsp white vinegar, 2 tbsp cornstarch, and 2-3 tsp pandan extract (taste as you go).
6. Whisk until stiff peaks form.
7. Spoon onto a baking tray, create a small well in the center, and bake at 225¬∞F for 75 min.
Let them cool in the oven with the door slightly open to avoid cracking. I took mine out after 15 min but you can wait much longer
8. Whip some heavy cream and zest in some lime or lemon, with as much or little sugar as you want. I use 100g but it was too sweet for me
9. Top with kiwi slices, a pinch of salt, and roasted nuts if you want crunch.

#pandan #vietnamesedessert #australiandessert #pavlova #pandandessert #asiancooking #vietnamesecooking

Salt a whole fish generously ‚Äî both sides and the cavity.
‚Ä®Let it sit 30 minutes (or up to 24 hours if you‚Äôre patient!)‚Ä®Then broil for 12 min, flip it CAREFULLY, and broil for another 6-10 min. Use your eyes and sense here. 

No broiler like me? No problem, set the oven at 450¬∞F until the skin crisps and the meat flakes like a dream.

I used branzino because my fish monger had it on deck.

‚≠êÔ∏è Save this for your next grocery run ‚≠êÔ∏è 

Cooking I found this trick while researching how soy sauce is actually made ‚Äî and it‚Äôs surprisingly simple. 

Just shake the bottle. If bubbles form and linger, that‚Äôs a sign of long fermentation and high soybean content. 

Cheaper sauces usually watered down and rushed - seen by bubbles that disappear quickly 

Fun fact: Kikkoman‚Äôs original family companies are older than the United States :O 

In Road to Michelin, I research and test cooking techniques to level up my home cooking skills ‚Äî and share what I learn with you. Got a tip or ingredient you want me to explore next? Just let me know :)
